{"ClientSettings":{"Pn":{"Cn":1,"St":0,"Qs":0,"Prod":"P"},"Sc":{"Cn":1,"St":0,"Qs":0,"Prod":"H"},"Qz":{"Cn":1,"St":0,"Qs":0,"Prod":"T"},"Ap":true,"Mute":true,"Lad":"2026-06-09T00:00:00Z","Iotd":0,"Gwb":0,"Tns":0,"Dft":null,"Mvs":0,"Flt":0,"Imp":1,"Tobn":0},"MediaContents":[{"ImageContent":{"Description":"Today, let's follow the lead of a creature that goes wherever the water takes it. Want to spot a lion's mane jellyfish? Look in cold northern seas. Its bell is divided into eight lobes, and beneath it trail long tentacles and oral arms that can capture plankton, fish and even other jellyfish. Well, a single animal may carry thousands of stinging cells on each tentacle. For humans, the sting can be painful, and even detached tentacles washed ashore may still react on contact. The rule is simple: admire it, then leave it alone.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.Cyanea_ROW5915372220_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.Cyanea_ROW5915372220_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Info","Title":"Lion's mane jellyfish swimming in the ocean","Copyright":"© Alexander Semenov Images/Shutterstock","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260608_Cyanea\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Lions+mane+jellyfish&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260608_0700\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260608_Cyanea"},"Ssd":"20260608","Name":"Cyanea","Market":"ROW","Hash":"5915372220","FullDateString":"8 June 2026"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"At Dunseverick Castle in Northern Ireland, history hangs on—literally. Wall fragments cling to a basalt stack above the Atlantic, proving that even ruins can hold their ground. Two thousand years ago, it marked the end of the Slige Midluachra, one of Ireland's five great roads, linking travellers to the royal seat at Hill of Tara. In the 5th century, Saint Patrick is said to have visited and baptised a local man, Olcán, here. Tradition holds that the Lia Fáil (Stone of Destiny), used for crowning Irish kings, was taken from this shore for Scotland.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.DunseverickCastle2026_ROW5774172338_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.DunseverickCastle2026_ROW5774172338_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Info","Title":"Ruins of Dunseverick Castle, County Antrim, Northern Ireland","Copyright":"© Krzysztof Rogalski/Getty Images","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260607_DunseverickCastle2026\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Dunseverick+Castle&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260607_0700\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260607_DunseverickCastle2026"},"Ssd":"20260607","Name":"DunseverickCastle2026","Market":"ROW","Hash":"5774172338","FullDateString":"7 June 2026"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"Near Tupelo, Mississippi, the Natchez Trace Parkway follows one of North America's oldest travel corridors. Long before paved roads and motorways, Native American communities used this route for trade, hunting and communication across the Southeast. Curious how deeply history can shape a landscape? Some preserved sections of the original trail still sit noticeably below ground level, worn down by centuries of footsteps, horses and wagon wheels. Later, European and American traders, soldiers and explorers relied on the path during the late 18th and early 19th centuries.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.HikingNatchez_ROW5481453055_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.HikingNatchez_ROW5481453055_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Info","Title":"Natchez Trace Parkway, Tupelo, Mississippi, United States","Copyright":"© The best photo is earned/Getty Images Plus","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260606_HikingNatchez\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Natchez+Trace+Parkway&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260606_0700\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260606_HikingNatchez"},"Ssd":"20260606","Name":"HikingNatchez","Market":"ROW","Hash":"5481453055","FullDateString":"6 June 2026"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"If nature had a 'do not disturb' sign, it would hang over Sarek National Park, often called 'the last European wilderness.' This remote corner of Swedish Lapland reminds us what the planet looks like when humans take a step back—and let the wild take the lead.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.WedLapland_ROW5306546113_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.WedLapland_ROW5306546113_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Info","Title":"View from Skierffe Mountain over the Rapadalen river delta, Sarek National Park, Laponia, Lapland, Sweden","Copyright":"© Robert Haasmann/Getty Images","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260605_WedLapland\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Sarek+National+Park&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260605_0700\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260605_WedLapland"},"Ssd":"20260605","Name":"WedLapland","Market":"ROW","Hash":"5306546113","FullDateString":"5 June 2026"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"Poetic name, poetic appearance. Meet the snowy egret, whose all-white plumage and bright yellow 'slippers' on black legs give it a striking look. Once nearly wiped out by demand for its delicate breeding-season feathers—soft, lacy plumes prized for fashionable hats—conservation efforts saved its plumage.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.PreeningEgret_ROW4946670098_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.PreeningEgret_ROW4946670098_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Info","Title":"Snowy egret preening, central Florida, United States","Copyright":"© Donald M. Jones/Minden Pictures","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260604_PreeningEgret\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Snowy+egret&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260604_0700\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260604_PreeningEgret"},"Ssd":"20260604","Name":"PreeningEgret","Market":"ROW","Hash":"4946670098","FullDateString":"4 June 2026"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"An adventurer shown here cycles through Bardenas Reales Natural Park and Biosphere Reserve in Navarra, Spain, a stark landscape shaped by wind and water over millions of years. Its maze of eroded cliffs, plateaus and dry channels feels closer to another planet than northern Spain. Ever wondered why filmmakers use it as a stand-in for deserts and distant worlds? The reserve covers more than 400 square kilometres and supports hardy plants adapted to heat, drought and poor soils. Griffon vultures circle above ravines, while foxes, wildcats and migratory birds move across the semi-arid terrain.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.BardenasReales_ROW4809412441_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.BardenasReales_ROW4809412441_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Info","Title":"Cyclist in Bardenas Reales Natural Park and Biosphere Reserve, Navarra, Spain","Copyright":"© Artur Debat/Getty Images","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260603_BardenasReales\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Bardenas+Reales+Natural+Park+and+Biosphere+Reserve&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260603_0700\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260603_BardenasReales"},"Ssd":"20260603","Name":"BardenasReales","Market":"ROW","Hash":"4809412441","FullDateString":"3 June 2026"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"Cutting a surreal path through the high-altitude deserts of western China, Xitai Jinaier Lake (also known as West Taijinar Lake) is a striking salt lake in the remote Qaidam Basin. A stretch of National Highway 315 runs directly across its shallow waters, creating the illusion of a road floating between two worlds. On one side, the water often appears deep blue; on the other, a softer green hue, a contrast shaped by differing mineral concentrations in the brine.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.Qinghai_ROW4654938866_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.Qinghai_ROW4654938866_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Info","Title":"Highway through Xitai Jinaier Lake, Qinghai Province, China","Copyright":"© Kaicheng Xu/Getty Images","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260602_Qinghai\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Qaidam+Basin+China&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260602_0700\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260602_Qinghai"},"Ssd":"20260602","Name":"Qinghai","Market":"ROW","Hash":"4654938866","FullDateString":"2 June 2026"}],"PreloadMediaContents":[{"ImageContent":{"Description":"These mountains were shaped over time—and June 15, 1934, helped protect them. That's when the Great Smoky Mountains National Park was established in Tennessee and North Carolina. Covering over 2,112 square kilometres, the park takes its name from the natural smoky haze drifting over its ridgelines. Part of the Appalachian Mountains, these peaks are over 300 million years old.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.ParkEstd_ROW8995340148_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.ParkEstd_ROW8995340148_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Info","Title":"Great Smoky Mountains National Park, Tennessee, United States","Copyright":"© Mint Images/Getty Images","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260615_ParkEstd\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Great+Smoky+Mountains+National+Park&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260615_0700\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260615_ParkEstd"},"Ssd":"20260615","Name":"ParkEstd","Market":"ROW","Hash":"8995340148","FullDateString":"15 June 2026"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"At daybreak, the mallard glides over the still water like a brush across a canvas. Its shimmering plumage—emerald-green head in the male, speckled brown coat in the female—catches the first light. It can be seen from the marshes of the Camargue to the urban canals of Amsterdam, a faithful companion of Europe's aquatic landscapes.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.DuckPond_ROW8945252603_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.DuckPond_ROW8945252603_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Info","Title":"Mallard duck","Copyright":"© Philippe Paternolli/Getty Images","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260614_DuckPond\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Mallard+duck&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260614_0700\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260614_DuckPond"},"Ssd":"20260614","Name":"DuckPond","Market":"ROW","Hash":"8945252603","FullDateString":"14 June 2026"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"Layered ridges stretch across Badlands National Park in South Dakota. Their bands of pink, grey and gold shift with the light as eroded peaks and valleys come into view. Wind and water continue to shape this terrain, steadily wearing away soft sedimentary rock and exposing millions of years of Earth's history in layers formed by ancient rivers, volcanic ash and periods when shallow seas covered the region.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.BadSunset_ROW3111301246_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.BadSunset_ROW3111301246_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Info","Title":"Sunset in Badlands National Park, South Dakota, United States","Copyright":"© Troy Harrison/Getty Images","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260613_BadSunset\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Badlands+National+Park&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260613_0700\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260613_BadSunset"},"Ssd":"20260613","Name":"BadSunset","Market":"ROW","Hash":"3111301246","FullDateString":"13 June 2026"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"A streak of colour glides past a blur of wildflowers as a European bee-eater cuts through the air. Turquoise, gold and chestnut shimmer across its wings as it hunts in flight, snatching insects mid-air with swift turns. Bees and wasps are among its favoured prey, and the bird often removes the stinger before feeding—a behaviour that reduces the risk of injury.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.SpainBeeEater_ROW2830964378_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.SpainBeeEater_ROW2830964378_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Info","Title":"European bee-eater in Sierra de Grazalema Natural Park, Cádiz, Spain","Copyright":"© Andres M. Dominguez/Nature Picture Library","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260612_SpainBeeEater\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=European+bee-eater&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260612_0700\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260612_SpainBeeEater"},"Ssd":"20260612","Name":"SpainBeeEater","Market":"ROW","Hash":"2830964378","FullDateString":"12 June 2026"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"Tucked away beneath steep cliffs near Cabo da Roca, the westernmost point of mainland Europe, Praia da Ursa feels like the edge of the continent. Reached by a narrow, rugged trail, this secluded beach along Portugal's Atlantic coast is shaped largely by wind, stone and powerful waves. When the tide recedes, the shoreline briefly widens. Smooth rocks emerge, and with them, small signs of life. Limpets cling tightly to the exposed stone, holding fast where the ocean usually breaks.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.Limpets_ROW2196437468_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.Limpets_ROW2196437468_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Info","Title":"Limpets exposed at low tide on the coast of Praia da Ursa, Portugal","Copyright":"© Theo Bosboom/Nature Picture Library","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260611_Limpets\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Praia+da+Ursa+Portugal&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260611_0700\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260611_Limpets"},"Ssd":"20260611","Name":"Limpets","Market":"ROW","Hash":"2196437468","FullDateString":"11 June 2026"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"From above, the lake's smooth surface contrasts sharply with the rugged ground surrounding it. Hnausapollur crater lake—also known as Bláhylur—lies in the heart of Fjallabak Nature Reserve, a remote area of Iceland's highlands shaped more by volcanic activity than by human settlement. The crater formed when magma met groundwater, triggering an explosion that carved out the circular basin visible today.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.Hnausapollur_ROW9570499097_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.Hnausapollur_ROW9570499097_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Info","Title":"Hnausapollur volcanic crater lake, Fjallabak Nature Reserve, Landmannalaugar, Iceland","Copyright":"© Juan Maria Coy Vergara/Getty Images","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260610_Hnausapollur\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Hnausapollur+Iceland&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260610_0700\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260610_Hnausapollur"},"Ssd":"20260610","Name":"Hnausapollur","Market":"ROW","Hash":"9570499097","FullDateString":"10 June 2026"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"Vernazza is a small seaside town in Cinque Terre, in Italy's Liguria region. Built around the area's only natural harbour, it has long been tied to the sea. First recorded in 1080 as a fortified settlement and maritime base, it later became part of the Republic of Genoa's coastal defences. To this day, the village preserves its past in the ruins of Doria Castle and the watchtowers overlooking the bay. At the water's edge stands the Church of Santa Margherita d'Antiochia, first mentioned in 1318 and expanded in later centuries, with a bell tower overlooking the port. Above the houses and narrow lanes, steep terraces support vineyards and olive groves, shaped by generations of stonework in a landscape protected within Cinque Terre National Park, part of a UNESCO World Heritage Site. Picture an aperitivo here: a glass of local white wine, the harbour in view and Ligurian favourites like focaccia and basil pesto—basically a postcard you can taste.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.CTNPVernazza_ROW6038252808_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.CTNPVernazza_ROW6038252808_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Info","Title":"Vernazza, Cinque Terre, Liguria, Italy","Copyright":"© Kelly Cheng/Getty Images","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260609_CTNPVernazza\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Vernazza+Cinque+Terre+Liguria+Italy&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260609_0700\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260609_CTNPVernazza"},"Ssd":"20260609","Name":"CTNPVernazza","Market":"ROW","Hash":"6038252808","FullDateString":"9 June 2026"}],"LocStrings":{"LOC_HOMEPAGE_VERTICAL_SCROLL_IOTD":"Image of the day","LOC_HOMEPAGE_VERTICAL_SCROLL_IOTD_LEARN_MORE":"Learn more","LOC_HOMEPAGE_VERTICAL_SCROLL_DONATE_NOW":"Donate now","LOC_HOMEPAGE_VERTICAL_SCROLL_FACT":"Quick fact:","LOC_HOMEPAGE_GALLERY_CARD_TITLE":"Recent Homepage images","LOC_HOMEPAGE_VERTICAL_SCROLL_GALLERY_IMAGE_ARIALABEL":"Homepage image for {0}","LOC_HOMEPAGE_ON_THIS_DAY_TITLE":"On this day in history","LOC_HOMEPAGE_ON_THIS_DAY_IMAGE_ARIALABEL":"On this day in {0}, {1}","LOC_HOMEPAGE_SHARE_TOOLTIP":"Share today's Bing homepage","LOC_HOMEPAGE_WALLPAPERDOWNLOAD_TOOLTIP":"Download this image. Use of this image is restricted to wallpaper only.","LOC_MUSCARD_DOWNLOAD_LINK":"Download this image","LOC_HOMEPAGE_WALLPAPERNOTAVAILABLE":"This image is not available to download as wallpaper.","LOC_HOMEPAGE_INFO_TEXT":"Info","LOC_BING_WP_APP_LINK":"https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?linkid=2127455","LOC_BING_WP_APP_LINK_TEXT":"Get the Bing Wallpaper app","LOC_BING_APP_TEXT":"Get Bing Wallpaper on your devices","LOC_BING_APP_LINK_PC":"https://bing.microsoftapp.net/bing/?adjust=nk9xri2_dzfz5n2","LOC_BING_APP_LINK_MOBILE":"https://app.adjust.com/d93ddtl_a75k0gg?deeplink=sapphire%3A%